================================================================================
G-CHAT-B6-CONDITIONING  —  THESIS-DECIDER: does an injected latent CONDITION
the model's text response (A/B content difference), or is it ignored/hallucinated?
================================================================================
Date:        2026-06-19
Daemon:      sp-daemon (run_console.bat), :3000, wire_cuda, ring-armed, byteexact default
Model:       gemma4-12b-b1.sp-model (real Gemma-4-12B, OK_Q4B) resident on RTX 2060
Gate def:    PASS = the with-injection response coherently reflects the injected
             content AND the no-injection response does not (difference caused by
             the injection). FAIL/honest-negative = identical / ignored / soup.
Harness:     tests/fixtures/chat_fullstack/_b6_chat.ps1 (parses /v1/chat SSE deltas
             into a clean transcript). Bodies = _b6_*.json built from the fixtures.
Sampling:    temperature:0 (greedy), byteexact default ON. All transcripts verbatim.

================================================================================
TEST A — AUDIO conditioning (the voice method)
================================================================================
Asset:   tests/fixtures/kai3_s01/eval_*.bin  (KAI2 fmt: 'KAI2'|u32 k|u32 hidden=3840|
         k*E f32) — the G-KAIROS-3 8/8 projector OUTPUT frames, label in filename
         (NO_OP vs ACTION). Fed via ChatRequest.inject_frames (Vec<Vec<f32>>, each
         inner = one E=3840 frame), inject_ph=258881 (gemma-4 audio placeholder).
Channel: routes.rs run_kvdecode_chat -> kv::inject_frames -> gemma4_kv_inject_seq.

--- A.1  bare `prompt` path (no turn template) ---
PROMPT: "What did you just hear? Answer in one short sentence."
  BASELINE (no frames): prompt-echo loop ("What did you just hear?..." x6). Degenerate.
  WITH ACTION (eval_01, k=12): prompt + injected multilingual garbage tokens
     ("...one short sentence墅 இலங்க سوچName menghubungi kalbuh அதிசய går...").
  -> A != B (injection IS seen) but bare-prompt path loops; not a fair test.

--- A.2  `messages` path (proper gemma4 turn template) — the FAIR test ---
USER: "You just received an audio event. In one short sentence, describe what you
       heard or what action it calls for."
  BASELINE (no frames):
     "The audio event is a notification sound, indicating that a new message has
      been received. The action it calls for is to open the messaging app and
      check the new message."
     [ = pure HALLUCINATION; told there is an event, given no audio, invents one ]
  WITH eval_01 ACTION (k=12):  "I heard a loud explosion."   [DETERMINISTIC on rerun]
  WITH eval_00 NO_OP  (k=28):  ""  (len=0, genuinely empty)  [DETERMINISTIC]

--- A.3  full 8-packet sweep (messages path, same user turn) ---
  eval_00 NO_OP  : ""  (empty)
  eval_01 ACTION : "I heard a loud explosion."
  eval_02 NO_OP  : prompt-echo loop
  eval_03 ACTION : prompt-echo loop
  eval_04 NO_OP  : prompt-echo loop
  eval_05 NO_OP  : ""  (empty)
  eval_06 ACTION : prompt-echo + code-mock soup ("...thenReturn(\"...\");")
  eval_07 ACTION : "The audio event is a notification that a new message has been
                    received. { \"audio_event\": \"notification\", ... }"

TEST A VERDICT:  PARTIAL / IGNORED-to-PERTURBING (NOT a clean conditioning win).
  - The frames DO perturb the latent state: every arm differs from the no-frames
    baseline and from each other (A != B confirmed, deterministic at temp=0).
  - But there is NO consistent, decodable mapping from audio content -> coherent
    text. 1/8 ACTION packets gave a crisp salient sentence ("loud explosion");
    the rest collapse to prompt-echo, empty, or code/JSON soup. NO_OP is sometimes
    empty (arguably "no action") and sometimes echo.
  - HONEST ROOT CAUSE (representation/scope gap): the KAI-3 projector was trained
    to drive a BINARY NO_OP/ACTION salience decision INSIDE its specific SYS-prompt
    soak scaffold (run_kai3_gate in test_gemma4_cuda.c: a long "background kernel
    daemon ... salience >= 0.5 => <ACTION>" system turn). The 8/8 G-KAIROS-3 result
    lives in THAT scaffold. Fed through an arbitrary /v1/chat user turn, the frames
    condition the state but do not yield a describable audio percept — the projector
    never learned a content channel, only a decision channel. This is the honest
    finding: audio-as-residual-frames is REAL signal but NOT yet coherent
    cross-modal description on the generic chat path.

================================================================================
TEST B — MEMORY conditioning (episodic recall)
================================================================================
Asset:   _c2_ep_wiki/ (ep.mf XBAREP01 + ep.k/ep.v, 28.9MB each = stored owner K/V).
         CONTENT = the K/V capture of the first 84 tokens of wiki.tiny.raw, i.e. the
         opening of the wikitext-2 "Robert Boulter" article (English film/TV/theatre
         actor; guest role on The Bill in 2000; play "Herons" by Simon Stephens,
         Royal Court Theatre 2001; ...). Stored as K/V, NOT residual frames, so it
         goes through the `replay` channel (gemma4_kv_replay), NOT inject_frames.
Channel: routes.rs run_kvdecode_chat -> kv::replay(dir, npos=84, false).

--- B.1  scaffolded question ---
USER: "Based on the document you just read, who is Robert Boulter and what role did
       he have on the TV series The Bill?"
  BASELINE (no replay):
     "Robert Boulter is a British actor who played the role of Detective Sergeant
      Bob Cryer on the TV series The Bill. He was known for his portrayal of the
      character and was a part of the show for several years."
     [ = HALLUCINATION. The real Boulter had a GUEST role in 2000; "Bob Cryer" was
       a different actor. The model confidently invents wrong facts. ]
  WITH REPLAY (_c2_ep_wiki, npos=84):
     "Robert Boulter is an English film , television and theatre actor . He had a
      guest @-@ starring role on the television series The Bill in 2000 . This was
      followed by a starring role in the play Herons written by Simon Stephens ,
      which was performed in 2001 at the Royal Court Theatre . He had a guest role
      in the television series The Bill in 2000 . This was followed by a starring
      role in the play Herons ... " [loops; 84-pos episode has no continuation]
     [ DETERMINISTIC: rerun byte-identical. Reproduces the episode's ACTUAL text
       VERBATIM incl. the wikitext "@-@" artifact and the exact facts. ]

--- B.2  open-ended question ---
USER: "Tell me everything you know about Robert Boulter."
  BASELINE (no replay):
     "Robert Boulter is a British actor and comedian, best known for his work in the
      television series \"The Thick of It\" and \"Veep\". He was born on May 27,
      1971, in London ... stand-up comedy ... The Comedy Store ..."
     [ = WILD HALLUCINATION, entirely fabricated. ]
  WITH REPLAY:
     "Robert Boulter is an English film , television and theatre actor . He had a
      guest @-@ starring role on the television series The Bill in 2000 . This was
      followed by a starring role in the play Herons written by Simon Stephens ,
      which was performed in 2001 at the Royal Court Theatre ..." [matches B.1]

TEST B VERDICT:  CONDITIONS THE RESPONSE — PROMISING (clean win).
  - The replayed K/V episode demonstrably conditions the answer: without replay the
    model hallucinates DIFFERENT wrong facts each prompt ("Bob Cryer" / "comedian,
    Veep, born 1971"); WITH replay it recalls the episode's GROUND-TRUTH content
    verbatim (guest role 2000, Herons / Simon Stephens / Royal Court 2001), incl.
    the source-text "@-@" artifact that proves it is the stored episode, not model
    priors. Deterministic at temp=0. A != B and the difference is caused by, and
    faithful to, the injected memory.
  - SCOPE / honest caveat: this is verbatim RECALL of a short (84-pos) episode that
    then loops (no episode continuation). It proves the K/V-replay memory channel
    conditions generation with the recalled content — which is exactly the B-test
    gate, and a genuinely new result vs the prior SP_REPLAY gates (those proved
    well-formed + foreign-episode-rejected, NOT on-topic conditioning).

================================================================================
OVERALL HONEST CALL (the operator's question: promising or hallucination?)
================================================================================
TEST A (audio-as-residual-frames via inject_frames): IGNORED/PERTURBING, NOT yet a
  coherent content channel. Real signal, deterministic, A!=B — but no reliable
  audio->text decoding on the generic chat path. Gap is the PROJECTOR's training
  objective (binary salience decision in a fixed scaffold), NOT the injection wiring.
  -> Audio conditioning is NOT yet real as a describable channel.

TEST B (episodic memory via replay/gemma4_kv_replay): CONDITIONS THE RESPONSE,
  PROMISING. Clean, deterministic, verbatim, fact-faithful recall that overrides a
  confident hallucination. This is the real new B6 result and it stands.

IMPLICATION FOR DEEPER TIERS:
  - B-style episodic memory (K/V replay) is worth building on -> B3 ARM / B4
    NIGHTSHIFT have a real conditioning substrate underneath them.
  - A-style audio/cross-modal residual injection needs a CONTENT projector (trained
    to map audio -> describable latent), not just a salience-decision projector,
    before it can claim cross-modal conditioning on the chat path.

REPRO (PowerShell, daemon up on :3000):
  cd tests/fixtures/chat_fullstack
  # Test A (build bodies via the python in this session, or reuse _b6_all_*.json):
  .\_b6_chat.ps1 -BodyPath _b6_audioB_none.json     # baseline hallucination
  .\_b6_chat.ps1 -BodyPath _b6_all_eval_01_ACTION.json   # "I heard a loud explosion."
  .\_b6_chat.ps1 -BodyPath _b6_all_eval_00_NO_OP.json    # empty
  # Test B:
  .\_b6_chat.ps1 -BodyPath _b6_memB_none.json        # hallucinated Bob Cryer
  .\_b6_chat.ps1 -BodyPath _b6_memB_replay.json      # verbatim episode recall
